comments.body: Aprox. un poco ms de un metro, estaba enroscada

@wolfgang_wuster check out the last one of the new photos posted, you can quite clearly distinguish a lacunolabial. Also on that photo the rostral scale has a triangular shape, not as rectangular as in Bothrocophias. Another thing I see is that the postocular stripe is slightly too wide and conspicuous for a female microphthalmus. What do you think?

Youre right @wolfgang_wuster, Bc. andianus tend to have a lacunolabial and a broad postocular stripe., but I still think this is B. monsignifer and not B. andianus.. The rostral scale is quite triangular whereas in andianus it is rectangular. Also the dorsal blotches in andianus are much wider and much closer to each other than in this specimen, and have a different shape (especially in the Bolivian andianus)
@jose_balderrama que tamao dira que tena esta serpiente?

@mossambica OK, you are right about the lacunolabial, so that seems to exclude *B. microphthalmus*. However, the other *Bothrocophias* we have not considered yet is *B. andianus*, which can have a lacunolabial and has a broad postocular stripe. 

Looking at that photo, all I see is a very robust, squat snake with a very broad head and very small eyes - it just does not look like a *Bothrops* to me...

@mossambica Hmmm.... not totally convinced - those keels look partly tubercular, and in any case, the difference between the scale shape of B. monsignifer and Bc. mircophthalmus and andianus are not all that great. @jose_balderrama are there any other photos of the same animal, e.g., in a different position or fleeing?
I'll put more pictures, but I did'n take other because I didn't want to disturb it
Interesting observation! I agree with Wolfgang, to my eye this appears to be *Bothrocophias*. However, I'm not confident enough to argue that as a solid identification.

comments.body: Most likely one of the Bothrops neuwiedi complex, species limits remain unclear.

@ariana34 It is somewhat similar to B. andianus but there are certain features that differentiate them. In Bothrocophias andianus the dorsal blotches generally consist of two separate oblique bars whereas the blotches in this specimen are the typical Bothrops-like triangular/trapezoidal blotches resembling a capital A. The head and neck pattern are also slightly different.
